Multiple class inheritance

Class a {}

Class b : a {}

Class c : a {}

Class x : b, c {}   <--- multiple inheritance

1) 	How does the order of base classes inherited matters?
	Class x : b , c {}
	vs Class x : c , b {} ?

	- It determines the order in which the base class subobjects are constructed and destructed. 
	- In terms of member access and ambiguities, 
		the order can affect which base class's members are used or overridden.

2)	Assume both Class b and Class c has member attribute int q.
	In this case int q is ambiguous in derived Class x.
		because both Class b and Class c has int q.
	If you try to access an ambiguous member attribute, it will result in compilation error.

3)	How to resolve ambiguity?
	 You need to specify which base class's q you are referring to (e.g., x.b::q or x.c::q), 
	or you need to resolve the ambiguity in the derived class.

